                  <persName id="t18310407-254-person1772">
                  THOMAS 
                  MARTIN
               <interp inst="t18310407-254-person1772" type="surname" value="MARTIN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310407-254-person1772" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310407-254-person1772" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I live in Lower-street, Islington, and am a <rs id="t18310407-254-viclabel1358" type="occupation">carpenter</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18310407-254-victim1771 t18310407-254-viclabel1358"></join>. On the 12th of March I lost a plane from my bench, in an unfinished house in <placeName id="t18310407-254-crimeloc1359">Chadwell-street</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18310407-254-crimeloc1359" type="placeName" value="Chadwell-street"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18310407-254-crimeloc1359" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18310407-254-off1356 t18310407-254-crimeloc1359"></join>- I left it safe at dinner-time, and did not miss it till about four o'clock; the prisoner was employed on the same premises - this is the plane.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310407-254-person1773">
                  HENRY 
                  FOWLER
               <interp inst="t18310407-254-person1773" type="surname" value="FOWLER"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310407-254-person1773" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310407-254-person1773" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I the service of Mr. Cordwell, a pawnbroker, in Exmouth-street, on the 12th of March the prisoner brought this plane to out shop - he pawned it for 6d, in the name of John Davies, for his father; he came twice to the shop with it.</p>
               <p>Cross-examined by MR. PHILLIPS. Q. Did you not on the first occasion doubt whether this was the person?</p>
               <p>A. I did not recognize him in the first instance, but that was on a different charge; his brother was brought up, and while he was gone for his brother another person asked if I knew him, and I said No - there is a brotherly likeness between them; I believe he is older, but not so tall- I did not express a doubt whether the prisoner was the person who pawned the plane; I did not entertain any doubt about that.</p>
               <p>THOMAS LOW. I am a constable. I took the prisoner into custody.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence. The pawnbroker said when I went with my brother, that I was the lad who pawned it. and I was not - he said I went there between three and five O'clock.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18310407-254-person1774">
                  THOMAS 
                  MARTIN
               <interp inst="t18310407-254-person1774" type="surname" value="MARTIN"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310407-254-person1774" type="given" value="THOMAS"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18310407-254-person1774" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             re-examined. Q. Did you know the prisoner's brother? A. Yes - he never worked there but one day, which was after the 12th of March, when his brother was ill - I think the pawnbroker's shop is half a mile from where I worked.</p>
               <p>The prisoner received a good character.</p>
               <p>
